  "prompt": "What's the origin of the expression \"Yippee Ki-Yay\"?",
  "response": "The expression \"Yippee Ki-Yay\" is widely recognized as a catchphrase popularized by the character John McClane, played by Bruce Willis, in the \"Die Hard\" film series. The phrase first appeared in the original 1988 \"Die Hard\" movie, where McClane uses it as a sort of taunt against his enemies.\n\nThe origin of the phrase itself is thought to stem from a playful variation of \u201cyippee,\u201d which is an exclamation of joy or excitement, combined with an informal term for a cowboy or Western-style expression. It reflects a sense of bravado and irreverence, fitting the tough and resourceful persona of McClane. \n\nWhile specific documentation of earlier uses of the exact phrase may be limited, it aligns with a broader tradition of cowboy slang and Western films. Over time, \"Yippee Ki-Yay\" has become emblematic of action movie culture and is often quoted in various contexts beyond \"Die Hard.\"",
